It is clear that the distributions Δf in Fig. 1 mix the two components of the electron distribution, namely, the thermal and non-thermal parts. To isolate the non-thermal contribution, one should consider the deviation of the electron distribution from the distribution at the steady-state temperature, ΔfNT≡f(E,Te,Tph)−fT(E,Te)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{\Delta }}f^{NT} \equiv f({\cal{E}},T_e,T_{ph}) - f^T({\cal{E}},T_e)$$\end{document}. Simply put, this is the “true” non-thermal part of the steady-state electron distribution, loosely referred in the literature as the “hot electron distribution”.

